WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.560
My name is Jill Mackay and these are my reflections from working for the last 10 years in veterinary

00:00:09.560 --> 00:00:16.959
science. This is actually a talk about environment management but when I'm talking about environment

00:00:16.959 --> 00:00:21.040
I want you to think about culture, that is the unwritten rules that a group of people

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:26.840
agree upon when they work in close proximity or exist in close proximity to one another.

00:00:26.840 --> 00:00:30.639
The central question for this talk is how do we make the vet school environment that

00:00:30.639 --> 00:00:37.799
I work in compatible with the PositConf environment. Not the same, you guys at PositConf are not

00:00:37.799 --> 00:00:42.200
going to be vets and my vets are not going to be fully data science practitioners but

00:00:42.200 --> 00:00:47.080
they should be able to talk to one another a little bit more than they currently do.

00:00:47.080 --> 00:00:51.320
I'm not going to spend a huge amount of time telling you guys what the PositConf environment

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:58.599
is like, you're there, I'm here in Edinburgh, but I think we do share some key ideas about

00:00:58.599 --> 00:01:03.200
good data science practice, its importance and we probably share some ideas about what

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:10.080
it looks like. Let me tell you a little bit about the Edinburgh vet environment. We are

00:01:10.080 --> 00:01:15.639
a very old vet school, we are called the Royal Dick School of Veterinary Studies, we have

00:01:15.639 --> 00:01:19.919
the word dick in our title and we just own it, we're that old, we're that respected,

00:01:19.919 --> 00:01:26.160
we are the dicks. We also have with us the Roslin Institute, you may know them from their

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:31.120
work with Dolly the sheep, from their work with COVID over the last couple of years and

00:01:31.120 --> 00:01:35.800
they have some of the best bioinformaticians in the world. I'm not talking about teaching

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:39.919
data science to these guys, they have forgotten more than I would ever learn.

00:01:39.919 --> 00:01:46.360
Well we also have our vets, these are both our students who have to be day one competent

00:01:46.360 --> 00:01:50.760
vets when they graduate, but also our clinicians who are amazing in the field of one world

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:57.480
health, the field of animal health, but they are very time poor and at Edinburgh we have

00:01:57.480 --> 00:02:02.000
both international impact but we also believe it's important that we make local impact as

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:07.919
well. This might seem really complicated and specific in terms of environments but I suspect

00:02:07.919 --> 00:02:13.919
it's really really similar to any of your workplace environments. We have subject specific

00:02:13.919 --> 00:02:19.240
experts who are really really good at something that they do, who need to know enough data

00:02:19.240 --> 00:02:25.000
science to talk to, for example, our bioinformaticians who are really really good at their data science

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:31.399
part of their role and not everybody has the same amount of time available to them to do

00:02:31.399 --> 00:02:35.880
data science, although it is creeping into everybody's role more and more.

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:41.559
I'm going to do three things in this talk, I'm going to talk about how we've changed

00:02:41.559 --> 00:02:45.320
our formal data science teaching, I'm going to talk about how we've changed workplace

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:50.559
culture and I'm going to talk about how we're trying to change some of our operational practice.

00:02:50.559 --> 00:02:54.720
At the end of this talk I'm really hoping there's going to be a long uncomfortable silence

00:02:54.720 --> 00:02:58.119
and then somebody's going to have to clear their throat and say we're really sorry Jill

00:02:58.119 --> 00:03:02.600
we've actually solved this already, it's all here on this lovely GitHub repository.

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:07.720
That's perfect, Posit will have paid for Edinburgh to get a consulting session and I get a lovely

00:03:07.720 --> 00:03:11.080
big tick in my performance management review at the end of the year.

00:03:11.080 --> 00:03:13.360
So that's what we're aiming for guys.

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:17.080
I suspect we're going to have a little bit more of a discussion about some of the barriers

00:03:17.080 --> 00:03:23.880
to institutional change that occur particularly within the data science context.

00:03:23.880 --> 00:03:26.720
We teach a huge number of students.

00:03:26.720 --> 00:03:31.960
We teach public engagement with massive open online courses, we're very big on open educational

00:03:31.960 --> 00:03:32.960
resources.

00:03:32.960 --> 00:03:36.759
Our undergraduates, we have our Bachelors of Veterinary Medicine and Surgery which takes

00:03:36.800 --> 00:03:39.639
on about 200 students a year-ish.

00:03:39.639 --> 00:03:44.800
We also have our Bachelors of Science in Agriculture and I just think it's important to highlight

00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:48.479
that we also have a Bachelors of Science in Veterinary Science which is what's called

00:03:48.479 --> 00:03:49.720
an exit degree.

00:03:49.720 --> 00:03:53.600
So if somebody enrols into the veterinary degree, gets to the clinical stage and they

00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:57.800
realise they don't want to do it, they can still exit recognising their learning.

00:03:57.800 --> 00:04:02.000
While we don't offer that as a degree to enrol on, it is a degree we offer and I think it's

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:03.960
a really important one actually.

00:04:03.960 --> 00:04:08.399
And that also includes the research project if they want to graduate with the BSc Honours,

00:04:08.399 --> 00:04:11.559
so there could be our teaching in there for example.

00:04:11.559 --> 00:04:15.720
Our postgraduate taught programmes are many and varied.

00:04:15.720 --> 00:04:20.320
We have a host of online programmes, distance learning programmes which we've been doing

00:04:20.320 --> 00:04:26.920
for many years and they all sort of serve a professional development kind of purpose.

00:04:26.920 --> 00:04:31.880
Often our students are those who are already working in the sector and are looking to upskill

00:04:31.880 --> 00:04:36.720
particularly their research because we are a research intensive university.

00:04:36.720 --> 00:04:40.720
We also have our postgraduate research, that's a little different from the North American

00:04:40.720 --> 00:04:41.720
context.

00:04:41.720 --> 00:04:46.399
Our postgrad research students are not enrolled in any classes, they sort of learn by doing

00:04:46.399 --> 00:04:51.519
the practice of research embedded within a research group.

00:04:51.519 --> 00:04:55.959
Within our undergraduate, so for the last 10 years we have seen a lot of curriculum

00:04:55.959 --> 00:05:01.480
overload with our vets, so we don't have the opportunity to completely teach them or change

00:05:01.480 --> 00:05:03.600
how we teach their data science.

00:05:03.600 --> 00:05:08.359
We do however offer optional R teaching within their research projects if the student and

00:05:08.359 --> 00:05:11.839
their host research group wants to go down that path.

00:05:11.839 --> 00:05:19.160
For our agricultural BSc's which we started in 2016, we do do all of our stats and data

00:05:19.160 --> 00:05:22.519
teaching in R from first year and that was really important to us.

00:05:22.519 --> 00:05:26.839
We recruited a lot of staff for that very purpose.

00:05:26.839 --> 00:05:31.640
Currently our ag BSc's are no longer recruiting, partly because of Covid and that's meant that

00:05:31.640 --> 00:05:37.920
we've lost those staff members who had that expertise in R teaching.

00:05:37.920 --> 00:05:41.640
Hold on to that, this is going to become a common narrative.

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:46.040
Within our taught programmes, as we were expanding our postgraduate taught programmes, we realised

00:05:46.040 --> 00:05:51.239
that we really needed to provide more research stats support, so we created a new role called

00:05:51.239 --> 00:05:57.799
a stats guru and they were pretty influential in trying to encourage every new programme

00:05:57.799 --> 00:06:03.519
and every new research course to do their teaching in R at a distance.

00:06:03.519 --> 00:06:07.640
I'm sure you're all familiar with some of the challenges that that can bring.

00:06:07.640 --> 00:06:14.480
We did try to support the campus with this, with our R at RDSVS resource, say that three

00:06:14.480 --> 00:06:20.640
times fast and part of our issue here is that our initial stats guru has since left

00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:25.359
us and our new stats guru is not quite such an R aficionado.

00:06:25.359 --> 00:06:30.519
So you may think we taught R forever more, but the big problems we're running into is

00:06:30.519 --> 00:06:34.040
we need skilled people to teach R and they keep leaving.

00:06:34.040 --> 00:06:39.079
We don't have the staff time for those who remain on programme to take up that R teaching

00:06:39.160 --> 00:06:43.160
because they can't themselves learn R quickly enough.

00:06:43.160 --> 00:06:48.760
We also have a recurring issue, which our programmes feed back to us, that student satisfaction

00:06:48.760 --> 00:06:53.600
suffers when they teach R and I think this is really important when we're talking about

00:06:53.600 --> 00:06:59.679
those students who are doing this for professional development.

00:06:59.679 --> 00:07:05.160
We realised that we kind of wanted to look at how we were talking about R in our culture

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:11.839
and one of our very skilled people, Ian Handel, created something called the Data Methods Club.

00:07:11.839 --> 00:07:15.440
If you've worked in any kind of university environment, a lab environment, you'll know

00:07:15.440 --> 00:07:20.480
how common it is to get an email saying I need more of this particular reagent to work

00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:22.720
at my experiment.

00:07:22.720 --> 00:07:26.959
Data Methods Club aims to make it as easy to ask for help with an analysis as it is

00:07:26.959 --> 00:07:30.160
to ask for an extra reagent.

00:07:30.160 --> 00:07:31.480
We have a range of approaches.

00:07:31.480 --> 00:07:37.440
We use a book club, which is more for slightly more comfortable R members, for example.

00:07:37.440 --> 00:07:44.160
We use parties, which are protected analysis in R time, yay, and these were really effective.

00:07:44.160 --> 00:07:50.079
This was booking out a room, inviting people to come to the room to do their analysis away

00:07:50.079 --> 00:07:54.480
from their emails, away from interruptions to their office, and we would always have

00:07:54.480 --> 00:07:59.399
some people who were pretty comfortable in R in the room just floating around ready to

00:07:59.399 --> 00:08:01.040
troubleshoot if needed.

00:08:01.040 --> 00:08:03.559
This was hugely, hugely successful.

00:08:03.559 --> 00:08:07.959
We also run occasional sessions and there's our aforementioned email help.

00:08:07.959 --> 00:08:11.600
If you take one thing away from this talk, take away the recurse center social rules.

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:15.679
We explicitly encourage all of our Data Methods Club members to follow them and it helps to

00:08:15.679 --> 00:08:19.679
make a really constructive learning environment.

00:08:19.679 --> 00:08:21.760
So we supported R forever more on campus.

00:08:21.760 --> 00:08:23.359
Well, not really.

00:08:23.359 --> 00:08:29.679
The global pandemic really impacted how we ran our Data Methods Club and staff time meant

00:08:29.720 --> 00:08:33.479
that we do struggle to make this run.

00:08:33.479 --> 00:08:38.599
It was supposed to be self-organizing, but it just hasn't really worked out that way.

00:08:38.599 --> 00:08:41.320
It does require somebody to organize it.

00:08:41.320 --> 00:08:46.719
Ian retired and is now building a house and sailing on his boat, and I tried to take some

00:08:46.719 --> 00:08:49.719
of this over, but I then went on match leave.

00:08:49.719 --> 00:08:56.640
So this is a recurring challenge that we have, this staff time problem.

00:08:56.640 --> 00:09:00.400
Something that I wouldn't have thought of 10 years ago, but has become more and more

00:09:00.400 --> 00:09:07.080
clear to me is that we need better data science in our operational practice.

00:09:07.080 --> 00:09:09.799
As a vet school, we have a lot of quality assurance.

00:09:09.799 --> 00:09:14.080
We have to guarantee that those vet students we were talking about earlier are what we

00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:16.599
call day one competent vets.

00:09:16.599 --> 00:09:18.559
So we need to know how we're teaching them.

00:09:18.559 --> 00:09:20.200
Are we teaching them effectively?

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:21.599
Are they happy with our teaching?

00:09:21.599 --> 00:09:23.280
All of these sorts of things.

00:09:23.280 --> 00:09:27.760
I, for my sins, I'm the vet school's new director of quality assurance and enhancement,

00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:33.640
and we're really interested in what data we can use to better inform our teaching.

00:09:33.640 --> 00:09:38.559
Teaching data is often managed by teaching organizations, and it is highly confidential.

00:09:38.559 --> 00:09:42.159
It cannot be shared in any capacity.

00:09:42.159 --> 00:09:49.440
So this, to me, is a really obvious place where we can use workflows to better support

00:09:49.440 --> 00:09:51.559
how we share practice.

00:09:51.599 --> 00:09:55.479
In Scotland, our quality assurance is what's called enhancement led.

00:09:55.479 --> 00:09:59.799
That means that we are all meant to share best practice and to just really reduce the

00:09:59.799 --> 00:10:02.239
workload of everybody else.

00:10:02.239 --> 00:10:06.599
This is starting to slide away from veterinary science and starting to talk more about the

00:10:06.599 --> 00:10:09.520
UK higher education sector as a whole.

00:10:09.520 --> 00:10:14.960
But something we are really trying to do, for example, is using shiny apps to show the

00:10:15.080 --> 00:10:21.440
data processing that we have got and that other institutions can use our shiny app to

00:10:21.440 --> 00:10:26.200
analyze, for example, their student survey data that they have got from the same place

00:10:26.200 --> 00:10:27.200
that we've got.

00:10:29.280 --> 00:10:34.359
So where are we in veterinary science with data science?

00:10:34.359 --> 00:10:37.119
Well, remind me in 10 years.

00:10:37.119 --> 00:10:37.919
I don't know.

00:10:37.919 --> 00:10:41.400
I don't know if I'm going to be here in 10 years, considering we keep losing skilled

00:10:41.400 --> 00:10:47.239
people. But my two key points that I have here is that we do keep losing skilled people

00:10:47.239 --> 00:10:54.000
and we do need more time to support staff so that they can teach data science practice.

00:10:55.440 --> 00:11:00.080
If we were to think about this as a Git repository, these are the issues that I would

00:11:00.080 --> 00:11:04.520
log. I would say that we're losing skilled people too often, that package updates far

00:11:04.520 --> 00:11:08.880
too often. Well, this is not actually a bug.

00:11:08.880 --> 00:11:11.359
This is a feature of working in a university.

00:11:11.359 --> 00:11:16.479
We are supposed to nurture talent and let that talent go off and do wonderful things.

00:11:17.679 --> 00:11:21.520
One of the things that we need to do better, and I would encourage anyone teaching data

00:11:21.520 --> 00:11:25.640
science to think really carefully about this, is to utilize extensive documentation and

00:11:25.640 --> 00:11:29.119
make it as easy as possible for somebody to take your course and run with it.

00:11:29.559 --> 00:11:33.640
I think Glasgow does this really, really well with their SciTeacher resource.

00:11:33.640 --> 00:11:34.880
Go and check that out.

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:37.200
I want to steal it and use it for worlds.

00:11:37.599 --> 00:11:41.119
And I think we're doing it reasonably well with our quality assurance work.

00:11:42.840 --> 00:11:47.719
The second issue, and this is one that comes up again and again when I'm talking to staff

00:11:47.719 --> 00:11:51.719
about whether or not they want to bring in more data science teaching, is that anything

00:11:51.719 --> 00:11:56.479
to do with R or coding is really complicated and time consuming and the students hate it.

00:11:57.520 --> 00:12:00.520
I think we need to make use of the many, many tools available.

00:12:00.520 --> 00:12:04.599
There's so much wonderful stuff going on at this conference and we need to use it.

00:12:04.919 --> 00:12:10.080
I personally am completely putting aside the tidyverse versus base R for teaching

00:12:10.080 --> 00:12:16.119
argument. I think we need to use it as easy as possible for those people who are time

00:12:16.119 --> 00:12:20.359
poor. I want to highlight here our Global Academy of Agriculture and Food Security does

00:12:20.359 --> 00:12:23.359
a really good short course on data science for farmers.

00:12:23.640 --> 00:12:26.159
And just take a look at how basic that is.

00:12:26.159 --> 00:12:29.599
And this is aimed at the public and it is really, really good.

00:12:30.599 --> 00:12:35.080
But this is the kind of level of data science that we're actually talking about when we

00:12:35.359 --> 00:12:37.559
are bringing in these postgraduate students.

00:12:38.039 --> 00:12:42.159
So making it as easy and accessible as possible is so important.

00:12:44.320 --> 00:12:49.599
My final issue that I'm going to log is I don't actually think this is currently possible

00:12:49.599 --> 00:12:51.520
in neoliberal higher education.

00:12:52.359 --> 00:12:54.080
Maybe this is a little bit controversial.

00:12:54.080 --> 00:12:55.080
I can't see the room.

00:12:55.520 --> 00:12:59.640
But I think this is actually a replication of the capitalism issue.

00:12:59.760 --> 00:13:04.400
If you're familiar with UK higher education, we are in a bit of crisis at the moment.

00:13:04.679 --> 00:13:07.840
We have been on strike since 2018, off and on.

00:13:08.200 --> 00:13:13.440
And we have a lot of issues with staff leaving, with staff being burnt out.

00:13:13.880 --> 00:13:19.000
And the traditional benefits of working in academia in the UK are being eroded.

00:13:19.320 --> 00:13:24.080
And a lot of very, very good people are going somewhere else because of it.

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:28.400
I don't know that there's an easy fix for this.

00:13:28.640 --> 00:13:32.840
And I don't know that anybody in this room necessarily has the power to change this.

00:13:33.159 --> 00:13:39.080
But it would be entirely remiss of me to talk about my reflections in the last 10 years

00:13:39.080 --> 00:13:44.880
without saying that UK academia is not currently a very friendly place for this.

00:13:45.440 --> 00:13:46.599
I am able to be here.

00:13:46.599 --> 00:13:51.200
I am able to do this because I have been incredibly lucky in my career to always have

00:13:51.200 --> 00:13:52.400
secure employment.

00:13:52.880 --> 00:13:54.760
Not everybody in academia has this.

00:13:54.919 --> 00:13:59.400
And without secure employment, people are not going to be able to have the time to

00:13:59.400 --> 00:14:03.400
develop these skills to a level where they can then teach them to others.

00:14:04.679 --> 00:14:08.440
I hope I'm preaching to the choir there, but I do think it's something that I have to

00:14:08.440 --> 00:14:14.559
explicitly say, if anyone's ever going to look at this talk again, this needs time and

00:14:14.559 --> 00:14:16.719
it needs support from a management level.

00:14:18.280 --> 00:14:21.760
OK, so now it's time for Indra's free consult time.

00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:24.000
Remember, I want that long, uncomfortable silence.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:27.799
And then I want somebody to tell me where you've already solved all of these issues.

00:14:28.119 --> 00:14:30.760
And thank you very much for listening.

00:14:36.960 --> 00:14:40.400
Thank you, Jill. I wish you could see we are very we're very happy with this talk.

00:14:40.400 --> 00:14:41.960
You did a great job. Thank you so much.

00:14:43.400 --> 00:14:45.640
We did have a question on Slido here.

00:14:46.119 --> 00:14:51.000
We had one that said just who leads those party sessions that you described?

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.039
Are they student led or is this something else?

00:14:53.640 --> 00:14:57.960
So, no, unfortunately, our parties are mainly led by me at the moment.

00:14:59.400 --> 00:15:05.359
We have really passionate PhD students who are really good at this sort of thing, but

00:15:05.359 --> 00:15:07.280
they rotate in and out of this so quickly.

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:15.479
And this parties are mainly aimed, mainly aimed at staff, supporting staff to get

00:15:15.479 --> 00:15:18.599
better and to do their analyses there.

00:15:19.400 --> 00:15:25.359
We do offer it to our postgraduate PhD students.

00:15:25.359 --> 00:15:27.599
They are always they're just kind of treated as staff.

00:15:27.599 --> 00:15:32.799
Our MRes students, our master's residential students, they kind of tend to come in.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:38.599
We have had the odd master of science on a taught programme come in, but not too many

00:15:38.599 --> 00:15:42.080
because they tend to be more on campus based.

00:15:42.239 --> 00:15:46.320
And so many of our MSc students are distance learning.

00:15:46.559 --> 00:15:51.400
So, yeah, it's it's mainly me, to be honest, I've actually just set up another further

00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:58.840
three today and it's me and anybody else who likes to hang around.

00:15:59.280 --> 00:16:02.679
And I think this is one of the big things is this isn't kind of really part of my

00:16:02.679 --> 00:16:05.159
role. This is just something I'm interested in.

00:16:05.159 --> 00:16:09.919
And again, without giving somebody like me the space to do something like this, you're

00:16:09.919 --> 00:16:12.119
just not going to upskill a group of people.

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:17.400
And I see there's another question on Slido, which is any tips to persuade academics

00:16:17.400 --> 00:16:20.479
who have been using paid commercial software for a long time to switch to R?

00:16:25.200 --> 00:16:29.919
For me, the really obvious argument is reproducibility.

00:16:30.280 --> 00:16:36.280
And I really like R Markdown and Quarto for those kind of things.

00:16:36.280 --> 00:16:41.760
I've been trying to get people into doing sort of package development to sort of show

00:16:41.760 --> 00:16:43.719
how that can support a workflow.

00:16:44.200 --> 00:16:52.599
And we have a big divide in the vet school between those who do really intensive data

00:16:52.599 --> 00:16:57.039
science and those who for whom data science is just a very small part of their role.

00:16:57.479 --> 00:17:02.520
And it's really, really difficult to get those for whom data science is just a small

00:17:02.520 --> 00:17:08.839
part of their role to move away from where they started way back when.

00:17:09.839 --> 00:17:14.280
This is something I would love to talk about in a huge amount of depth, and I will try

00:17:14.280 --> 00:17:18.079
to pull myself back. I think a lot of this is actually how we teach science, because

00:17:18.079 --> 00:17:20.000
we teach science as this immutable thing.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:24.439
And I think we need to think more critically about the underlying philosophies of science

00:17:24.439 --> 00:17:27.319
and show how important it is to adapt as we go.

00:17:27.719 --> 00:17:33.479
My biggest tip is to lead with reproducibility and the time saving of that.

00:17:33.680 --> 00:17:39.839
But to be honest with you, a lot of academics are still at the stage of like color coding

00:17:39.839 --> 00:17:45.599
an Excel spreadsheet to demonstrate who coded what data or something like that.

00:17:45.880 --> 00:17:47.880
And that's a problem.

